 Blessing MasakadzaÂ SENIOR STAFF WRITERmasakadzab@dailynews.co.zwTWO people have been arrested for allegedly printing fake Covid-19 certificates and selling them to travellers at Roadport Bus Station in Harare.Takesure Kanyani and Tariro Chimhavi are accused of forging the certificates and inscribing names of different health centres as the issuers of the documents before selling them to travellers.The duo was not asked to plead to allegations of forgery when they appeared before Harare magistrate Barbra Mateko.They were remanded in custody to today for bail application.Reports are that on January 4 at around 10am, detectives received information that the two were printing fake Covid-19 certificates at Peacock Saloon along Jason Moyo Avenue in the capital and selling them to travellers at Roadport.The cops went there and recovered four forged certificates in different names purportedly issued by one Doctor T Moyo of Parktown Hospital from Kanyani.Prosecutor Owen Safuri told the court that Kanyani allegedly indicated that there were more certificates in the computer.Kanyani voluntarily printed more certificates purported to have been issued by Sally Mugabe Central Hospital, Mello Health and Pathcare Molecular Pathology.It is alleged Kanyani is the owner of the computers used to forge the documents, which belonged to Chimhavi.Police then arrested Chimhavi, who admitted to being the source of the forged certificates and also showed the detectives more fake documents in a mobile phone.The detectives went to Parktown Hospital where they verified that the certificates did not originate from the institution. Sponsored Links

